          "body": "Ezekiel 32 is the seventh and final oracle against Egypt in a sustained prophetic sequence (chapters 29-32). The earlier oracles announced what Babylon would do to Egypt (29:1-16), lamented the broken reed that Pharaoh had been to Israel (29:6-7), described the land's forty-year desolation (29:10-12), and compared Pharaoh to a great tree cut down (chapter 31). Chapter 32 does not repeat those themes — it finalizes them. The lament form (*qinah*) signals that whatever Egypt was in the land of the living is now past tense. The Sheol-vision signals something more: Egypt's destruction is not a novel tragedy in history but the last member of a long series — every empire that built its throne on terror has preceded Egypt in this descent. The pastoral logic for the exilic community is unsentimental: stop looking south toward Egypt for rescue. The gallery is already full, and there is a reserved space for Pharaoh."
